Capacitors are electronic components that store electrical energy in an electric field. They consist of two conductive plates separated by an insulating material called a dielectric. When a voltage is applied across the plates, electric charge accumulates on the plates, creating an electric field between them.
When word line is not charged gates are closed and capacitor have energy in it. Even when gate is closed we will have charge leakage in capacitor. Change will go out of capacitor. That’s why we need to continuously write information to cells.
Charge leakage refers to the gradual loss of stored charge in a capacitor over time. In an ideal capacitor, charge would remain constant once it's stored, but in real-world situations, various factors contribute to charge leakage.
